@Slow Hand Brad, to explain this for when you wake up - Adam mentioned that you and I had both mentioned a similar point on some feedback, but referred to you as “Brad”. I thought “who the fuck is Brad?” before making the connection, but already you now exist in my mind as two different people:

Bradley - concise, considered. Digital notes interlinked by theme, subject, and metadata.

Brad - meathead jock, captain of the football team. Bogwashes nerds (whatever you call it when you hold someone’s ankle and flush their head in a toilet).

@Eric Martin thanks for your reply man, re: clippers vs compression......yes i am familiar with that. I dont use compression for dynamics control either....you may have heard of the "clip to zero" strategy? i do a similar thing but then output my limiters/clippers at -6db instead of 0. Its similar to what johns doing just catching peaks and not squashing the life out of everythin....mike dean does it too IIRC. 

Re: spectral shaper : I didnt actually spot jon using his spectral shaper in that 1-6khz region, i saw it in the low mids....so having heard you and @oaklandmatt both mention it ...it seems hes defo already using this high mid scoop trick then! Ill still research the maths of the lufs algo because i like to really understand the psycho-acoustics and science of these sorts of things. Im after the ultimate mix in this life, lol .....i come from underground club music, where drums and bass and a sweet vocal are everything so its a constant balance/re-balance between lows/mids and highs as i learn more advanced techniques

..re: jons mix yesterday and clipping, and you mention clipping the attack portion of a sounds adsr , did you notice how much he uses transient shapers on almost everything? v clever. Personally, i love transients and fight hard to keep them and jons trick of putting a transient shaper after a clipper/limiter has been a revelation....(thanks @oaklandmatt , that gem came from your LWMR) .....bruce swedien said compression is for children, and i believe he evangelised about not killing transients ...i love a transient shaper and a clipper ....compressor , not so much.

@Gazing Wrmth | Mixes & Masters I’m pretty much exclusively in cans and i second all of what Noah said. Additionally, sonarworks for your headphones is definitely worth it esp. for only 70 USD. It will smear transients a bit, but you can get over that if you reference well. Mix quiet and you won’t be disappointed. 

Forgot to mention, because DT 770s are closed back, making sure you have a good seal and taking breaks are critical. You need a 15 minute break for every hour you put in on cans, bare minimum IMO. Without that, attention loss and fatigue kick in. 

Tools like tonal balance control 2 are important. I recommend setting up a Pro-MB with 3-5 bands across the entire frequency range but make them all neutral with no compression. Sub, low, mid, high mid, top end. You can monitor specific ranges now. And for sub/low end, you can turn the gain up on your headphone mix a bit, isolate the low end, and you can hear it a bit better. Make sure you turn your headphones down a bit before you un-solo the low or the sub, but this has helped me massively

@Joe Thomas I know I threw a lot out there, hopefully something will trigger a creative solution!

When something doesn’t seem to ever be loud enough I try to mix it with the drums by themselves (so drums and bass) then slowly bring everything else in and make sure the bass doesn’t get lost with each addition.

Last thing - mixing bass NOT soloed can really help. You might push the knobs a lot farther that way if you’re actually trying to get it to push through a dense mix as opposed to by itself.

This is something I’m still figuring out. I went through phases of not enough bass, too much bass, and now trying to find a balance. 

@Maxim mentioned how Manny’s Kendrick mixes don’t have too much going on at 40hz (I think this is the case on many of his mixes), but his basses or kicks sound HUGE. Not having too much lows and great balancing is probably what allows his mixes to have the loudness he does. 

While Jon’s philosophy is to save and cherish the low low subs, when you look at the meter, they’re not hitting like crazy amount. But I still feel that low low, which I also love.

if you happen to have a MWTM subscription Eddie Kramer discusses exactly this as being the necessary process when they had to commit everything to 4 tracks (i think) forJimi Hendrix-  are you experienced . Its an inspiring listen to hear what they achoeved that way..
i know you mention the pie comp a lot, kramer Loves that comp lol, he talks about smashing the pianos and guitars with it.

@cian riordan coincidentally i was just watching st,Vincent’s production process video on reverb over the last few days and wondered how much of what she does ....with the verbs and delays comes baked in to you ...and if so how you approached it as a mixer. I wondered if it sort of tied your hands a bit for possible decisions...but from your post above about baking it in early  ....i guess it suits just fine. V Dope

@Juliette Ok having heard the track, there’s a solo synth bass in there which is well designed sonically, when that drops out and the bass guitar comes back in, everything from about 60-70 cycles and below disappears except for the kick. So yeah I’d first try pumping low end into it, be it with EQ or subharmonic, followed by some (a lot) of compression. I’m sure better people here have a better way to do this. 

The DI itself doesn’t have any overtones other than stuff you’re finding unflattering, so you could try mult’ing the DI signal out to an amp sim (even some guitar amps work here) to fill out the spectrum that the guitars aren’t fulfilling 

I’d also say the bass drum could use some augmenting of the low end  and maybe a bit of length in order to emphasise that impact. Because the synth bass atm has all the power, and isn’t omnipresent, so it’s leaving the rest of the arrangement even _more_ neutered as a result

Thanks so much for all the replies everyone, really appreciate it, lots of good stuff here 🙏

@aliberger @Rob Domos totally feel you on the pitch-envelope side of things, that part actually makes a lot of sense to me.

@chrissoremI hear you about not overthinking and keeping it fun, I’m definitely guilty of going too deep sometimes lol.

What I’m mainly stuck on though is just getting clear transients when a few drums are going at once. Low end is fine (everything non-kick is high-passed), but the top end is where my kick transient sometimes gets masked by loops/percs. That’s why I mentioned the tiny time-offset thing, not big shifts, just few ms to see if it helps the transient poke through without messing up the groove @thegreatcarsoni. Not sure if that’s considered bad practice, but sometimes it feels like it helps.
